Three surface barrier detectors with a
sensitive thickness of 1 mm served to measure the
forward-angle data.
Two position-sensitive detectors, each
covering an angular range of 12degr., were used at
backward angles.
Three fixed detectors, at 161. degr. and at +-15degr.,
served as monitors of the target, beam intensity and
incident beam direction.
The measurements at the energies higher than
50 MeV were made with telescopes of 2 or 3 fully
depleted detectors of 1 mm sensitive thickness stacked
in series to allow for the greater range of scattered
alpha -particles.
Uncertainty in the absolute normalization.
The target thickness was determined by energy-loss
measurements of 5.9 MeV alpha-particles. The estimated
accurancy is 20%. To obtain a consistent normalization
of cross section data, the measurements were made for
the different targets overlapping in energy and angle.
Uncertainty from statistics and
angle accurancy
The injector cyclotron facility
The Ca targets were fabricated by evaporating natural
Ca (with a 40Ca content of 96.6%) onto self-supporting
carbon foils of 20 mu-g/cm2 thickness. Target
densities of 200-400 mu-g/cm2 were used.
The 50Ti and the 52Cr targets consisted of
self-supporting foils. These isotopically enriched
targets contained 83.2% 50Ti, 12.4% 48Ti and 99.9% 52Cr
